[src:ospf-routing/dijkstra-s-algorithm] Dijkstra's algorithm finds the shortest path from a given source node to every other node.
[src:ospf-routing/dijkstra-s-algorithm] It can be used to find the shortest path to a specific destination node, by terminating the algorithm after determining the shortest path to that node.
[src:ospf-routing/dijkstra-s-algorithm] For example, if the nodes of the graph represent cities, and the costs of edges represent the distances between pairs of cities connected by a direct road, then Dijkstra's algorithm can be used to find the shortest route between one city and all other cities.
[src:ospf-routing/dijkstra-s-algorithm] A common application of shortest path algorithms is network routing protocols, most notably IS-IS (Intermediate System to Intermediate System) and OSPF (Open Shortest Path First).
[src:ospf-routing/dijkstra-s-algorithm] It is also employed as a subroutine in algorithms such as Johnson's algorithm.
[src:ospf-routing/dijkstra-s-algorithm] The algorithm uses a min-priority queue data structure for selecting the shortest paths known so far.
[src:ospf-routing/dijkstra-s-algorithm] Before more advanced priority queue structures were discovered, Dijkstra's original algorithm ran in $\Theta (|V|^{2})$ time, where $|V|$ is the number of nodes.
[src:ospf-routing/dijkstra-s-algorithm] Fredman & Tarjan 1984 proposed a Fibonacci heap priority queue to optimize the running time complexity to $\Theta (|E|+|V|\log |V|)$ , where $|E|$ is the number of edges.
[src:ospf-routing/dijkstra-s-algorithm] This is asymptotically the fastest known single-source shortest-path algorithm for arbitrary directed graphs with unbounded non-negative weights.
[src:ospf-routing/dijkstra-s-algorithm] However, specialized cases (such as bounded/integer weights, directed acyclic graphs etc.) can be improved further.
[src:ospf-routing/dijkstra-s-algorithm] If preprocessing is allowed, algorithms such as contraction hierarchies can be up to seven orders of magnitude faster.
[src:ospf-routing/dijkstra-s-algorithm] Dijkstra's algorithm is commonly used on graphs where the edge weights are positive integers or real numbers.
[src:ospf-routing/dijkstra-s-algorithm] It can be generalized to any graph where the edge weights are partially ordered, provided the subsequent labels (a subsequent label is produced when traversing an edge) are monotonically non-decreasing.
[src:ospf-routing/dijkstra-s-algorithm] In many fields, particularly artificial intelligence, Dijkstra's algorithm or a variant offers a uniform cost search and is formulated as an instance of the more general idea of best-first search.
[src:ospf-routing/dijkstra-s-algorithm] — Edsger Dijkstra, in an interview with Philip L.
[src:ospf-routing/dijkstra-s-algorithm] Dijkstra thought about the shortest path problem while working as a programmer at the Mathematical Center in Amsterdam in 1956.
[src:ospf-routing/dijkstra-s-algorithm] He wanted to demonstrate the capabilities of the new ARMAC computer.
[src:ospf-routing/dijkstra-s-algorithm] His objective was to choose a problem and a computer solution that non-computing people could understand.
[src:ospf-routing/dijkstra-s-algorithm] He designed the shortest path algorithm and later implemented it for ARMAC for a slightly simplified transportation map of 64 cities in the Netherlands (he limited it to 64, so that 6 bits would be sufficient to encode the city number).
[src:ospf-routing/dijkstra-s-algorithm] A year later, he came across another problem advanced by hardware engineers working on the institute's next computer: minimize the amount of wire needed to connect the pins on the machine's back panel.
[src:ospf-routing/dijkstra-s-algorithm] As a solution, he re-discovered Prim's minimal spanning tree algorithm (known earlier to Jarník, and also rediscovered by Prim).
[src:ospf-routing/dijkstra-s-algorithm] Dijkstra published the algorithm in 1959, two years after Prim and 29 years after Jarník.
[src:ospf-routing/dijkstra-s-algorithm] The algorithm requires a starting node, and computes the shortest distance from that starting node to each other node.
[src:ospf-routing/dijkstra-s-algorithm] Assign to every node a distance from start value: for the starting node, it is zero, and for all other nodes, it is infinity, since initially no path is known to these nodes.
[src:ospf-routing/dijkstra-s-algorithm] During execution, the distance of a node *N* is the length of the shortest path discovered so far between the starting node and *N*.
[src:ospf-routing/dijkstra-s-algorithm] From the unvisited set, select the current node to be the one with the smallest (finite) distance; initially, this is the starting node (distance zero).
[src:ospf-routing/dijkstra-s-algorithm] If the unvisited set is empty, or contains only nodes with infinite distance (which are unreachable), then the algorithm terminates by skipping to step 6.
[src:ospf-routing/dijkstra-s-algorithm] If the only concern is the path to a target node, the algorithm terminates once the current node is the target node.
[src:ospf-routing/dijkstra-s-algorithm] For the current node, consider all of its unvisited neighbors and update their distances through the current node; compare the newly calculated distance to the one currently assigned to the neighbor and assign the smaller one to it.
[src:ospf-routing/dijkstra-s-algorithm] For example, if the current node *A* is marked with a distance of 6, and the edge connecting it with its neighbor *B* has length 2, then the distance to *B* through *A* is 6 + 2 = 8.
[src:ospf-routing/dijkstra-s-algorithm] If B was previously marked with a distance greater than 8, then update it to 8 (the path to B through A is shorter).
[src:ospf-routing/dijkstra-s-algorithm] Otherwise, keep its current distance (the path to B through A is not the shortest).
[src:ospf-routing/dijkstra-s-algorithm] After considering all of the current node's unvisited neighbors, the current node is removed from the unvisited set.
[src:ospf-routing/dijkstra-s-algorithm] Thus a visited node is never rechecked, which is correct because the distance recorded on the current node is minimal (as ensured in step 3), and thus final.
[src:ospf-routing/dijkstra-s-algorithm] Once the loop exits (steps 3–5), every visited node contains its shortest distance from the starting node.
[src:ospf-routing/dijkstra-s-algorithm] The shortest path between two intersections on a city map can be found by this algorithm using pencil and paper.
[src:ospf-routing/dijkstra-s-algorithm] Every intersection is listed on a separate line: one is the starting point and is labeled (given a distance of) 0.
[src:ospf-routing/dijkstra-s-algorithm] Every other intersection is initially labeled with a distance of infinity.
[src:ospf-routing/dijkstra-s-algorithm] This is done to note that no path to these intersections has yet been established.
[src:ospf-routing/dijkstra-s-algorithm] At each iteration one intersection becomes the current intersection.
[src:ospf-routing/dijkstra-s-algorithm] For the first iteration, this is the starting point.
[src:ospf-routing/dijkstra-s-algorithm] From the current intersection, the distance to every neighbor (directly-connected) intersection is assessed by summing the label (value) of the current intersection and the distance to the neighbor and then relabeling the neighbor with the lesser of that sum and the neighbor's existing label.
[src:ospf-routing/dijkstra-s-algorithm] I.e., the neighbor is relabeled if the path to it through the current intersection is shorter than previously assessed paths.
[src:ospf-routing/dijkstra-s-algorithm] If so, mark the road to the neighbor with an arrow pointing to it, and erase any other arrow that points to it.
[src:ospf-routing/dijkstra-s-algorithm] After the distances to each of the current intersection's neighbors have been assessed, the current intersection is marked as visited.
[src:ospf-routing/dijkstra-s-algorithm] The unvisited intersection with the smallest label becomes the current intersection and the process repeats until all nodes with labels less than the destination's label have been visited.
[src:ospf-routing/dijkstra-s-algorithm] Once no unvisited nodes remain with a label smaller than the destination's label, the remaining arrows show the shortest path.
[src:ospf-routing/dijkstra-s-algorithm] In the following pseudocode, dist is an array that contains the current distances from the *source* to other vertices, i.e. dist[*u*] is the current distance from the source to the vertex *u*.
[src:ospf-routing/dijkstra-s-algorithm] The prev array contains pointers to previous-hop nodes on the shortest path from source to the given vertex (equivalently, it is the *next-hop* on the path *from* the given vertex *to* the source).
[src:ospf-routing/dijkstra-s-algorithm] The code u ← vertex in *Q* with min dist[u], searches for the vertex *u* in the vertex set *Q* that has the least dist[*u*] value.
[src:ospf-routing/dijkstra-s-algorithm] Graph.Distance(*u*,*v*) returns the length of the edge joining (i.e. the distance between) the two neighbor-nodes *u* and *v*.
[src:ospf-routing/dijkstra-s-algorithm] The variable *alt* on line 14 is the length of the path from the *source* node to the neighbor node *v* if it were to go through *u*.
[src:ospf-routing/dijkstra-s-algorithm] If this path is shorter than the current shortest path recorded for *v*, then the distance of *v* is updated to *alt*.
[src:ospf-routing/dijkstra-s-algorithm] To find the shortest path between vertices *source* and *target*, the search terminates after line 10 if *u* = *target*.
[src:ospf-routing/dijkstra-s-algorithm] Now sequence *S* is the list of vertices constituting one of the shortest paths from *source* to *target*, or the empty sequence if no path exists.
[src:ospf-routing/dijkstra-s-algorithm] A more general problem is to find all the shortest paths between *source* and *target* (there might be several of the same length).
[src:ospf-routing/dijkstra-s-algorithm] Then instead of storing only a single node in each entry of prev[] all nodes satisfying the relaxation condition can be stored.
[src:ospf-routing/dijkstra-s-algorithm] For example, if both *r* and *source* connect to *target* and they lie on different shortest paths through *target* (because the edge cost is the same in both cases), then both *r* and *source* are added to prev[*target*].
[src:ospf-routing/dijkstra-s-algorithm] When the algorithm completes, prev[] data structure describes a graph that is a subset of the original graph with some edges removed.
[src:ospf-routing/dijkstra-s-algorithm] Its key property is that if the algorithm was run with some starting node, then every path from that node to any other node in the new graph is the shortest path between those nodes graph, and all paths of that length from the original graph are present in the new graph.
[src:ospf-routing/dijkstra-s-algorithm] Then to actually find all these shortest paths between two given nodes, a path finding algorithm on the new graph, such as depth-first search would work.
[src:ospf-routing/dijkstra-s-algorithm] A min-priority queue is an abstract data type that provides 3 basic operations: add_with_priority(), decrease_priority() and extract_min().
[src:ospf-routing/dijkstra-s-algorithm] As mentioned earlier, using such a data structure can lead to faster computing times than using a basic queue.
[src:ospf-routing/dijkstra-s-algorithm] Notably, Fibonacci heap or Brodal queue offer optimal implementations for those 3 operations.
[src:ospf-routing/dijkstra-s-algorithm] Instead of filling the priority queue with all nodes in the initialization phase, it is possible to initialize it to contain only *source*; then, inside the `**if** *alt* < dist[*v*]` block, the decrease_priority() becomes an add_with_priority() operation.
[src:ospf-routing/dijkstra-s-algorithm] Yet another alternative is to add nodes unconditionally to the priority queue and to instead check after extraction (`*u* ← *Q*.extract_min()`) that it isn't revisiting, or that no shorter connection was found yet in the `if alt < dist[v]` block.
[src:ospf-routing/dijkstra-s-algorithm] This can be done by additionally extracting the associated priority `*p*` from the queue and only processing further `**if** *p* == dist[*u*]` inside the `**while** *Q* is not empty` loop.
[src:ospf-routing/dijkstra-s-algorithm] These alternatives can use entirely array-based priority queues without decrease-key functionality, which have been found to achieve even faster computing times in practice.
[src:ospf-routing/dijkstra-s-algorithm] However, the difference in performance was found to be narrower for denser graphs.
[src:ospf-routing/dijkstra-s-algorithm] To prove the correctness of Dijkstra's algorithm, mathematical induction can be used on the number of visited nodes.
[src:ospf-routing/dijkstra-s-algorithm] The base case is when there is just one visited node, source.
[src:ospf-routing/dijkstra-s-algorithm] Its distance is defined to be zero, which is the shortest distance, since negative weights are not allowed.
[src:ospf-routing/dijkstra-s-algorithm] Assuming that the hypothesis holds for k visited nodes, to show it holds for $k+1$ nodes, let u be the next visited node, i.e. the node with minimum `dist[u]`.
[src:ospf-routing/dijkstra-s-algorithm] The claim is that `dist[u]` is the shortest distance from source to u.
[src:ospf-routing/dijkstra-s-algorithm] If a shorter path were available, then this shorter path either contains another unvisited node or not.
[src:ospf-routing/dijkstra-s-algorithm] For all other visited nodes v, the `dist[v]` is already known to be the shortest distance from source, because of the inductive hypothesis, and these values are unchanged.
[src:ospf-routing/dijkstra-s-algorithm] After processing u, it is still true that for each unvisited node w, `dist[w]` is the shortest distance from source to w using visited nodes only.
[src:ospf-routing/dijkstra-s-algorithm] Any shorter path that did not use u, would already have been found, and if a shorter path used u it would have been updated when processing u.
[src:ospf-routing/dijkstra-s-algorithm] After all nodes are visited, the shortest path from source to any node v consists only of visited nodes.
[src:ospf-routing/dijkstra-s-algorithm] Therefore, `dist[v]` is the shortest distance.
[src:ospf-routing/dijkstra-s-algorithm] Bounds of the running time of Dijkstra's algorithm on a graph with edges E and vertices V can be expressed as a function of the number of edges, denoted $|E|$ , and the number of vertices, denoted $|V|$ , using big-O notation.
[src:ospf-routing/dijkstra-s-algorithm] The complexity bound depends mainly on the data structure used to represent the set Q.
[src:ospf-routing/dijkstra-s-algorithm] In the following, upper bounds can be simplified because $|E|$ is $O(|V|^{2})$ for any simple graph, but that simplification disregards the fact that in some problems, other upper bounds on $|E|$ may hold.
[src:ospf-routing/dijkstra-s-algorithm] where $T_{\mathrm {dk} }$ and $T_{\mathrm {em} }$ are the complexities of the *decrease-key* and *extract-minimum* operations in Q, respectively.
[src:ospf-routing/dijkstra-s-algorithm] The simplest version of Dijkstra's algorithm stores the vertex set Q as a linked list or array, and edges as an adjacency list or matrix.
[src:ospf-routing/dijkstra-s-algorithm] In this case, extract-minimum is simply a linear search through all vertices in Q, so the running time is ${\textstyle \Theta (|E|+|V|^{2})=\Theta (|V|^{2})}$ .
[src:ospf-routing/dijkstra-s-algorithm] To perform decrease-key steps in a binary heap efficiently, it is necessary to use an auxiliary data structure that maps each vertex to its position in the heap, and to update this structure as the priority queue Q changes.
[src:ospf-routing/dijkstra-s-algorithm] With a self-balancing binary search tree or binary heap, the algorithm requires ${\textstyle \Theta ((|E|+|V|)\log |V|)}$ time in the worst case; for connected graphs this time bound can be simplified to ${\textstyle \Theta (|E|\log |V|)}$ .
[src:ospf-routing/dijkstra-s-algorithm] The Fibonacci heap improves this to ${\textstyle \Theta (|E|+|V|\log |V|)}$ .
[src:ospf-routing/dijkstra-s-algorithm] In common presentations of Dijkstra's algorithm, initially all nodes are entered into the priority queue.
[src:ospf-routing/dijkstra-s-algorithm] This is, however, not necessary: the algorithm can start with a priority queue that contains only one item, and insert new items as they are discovered (instead of doing a decrease-key, check whether the key is in the queue; if it is, decrease its key, otherwise insert it).
[src:ospf-routing/dijkstra-s-algorithm] This variant has the same worst-case bounds as the common variant, but maintains a smaller priority queue in practice, speeding up queue operations.
[src:ospf-routing/dijkstra-s-algorithm] Moreover, not inserting all nodes in a graph makes it possible to extend the algorithm to find the shortest path from a single source to the closest of a set of target nodes on infinite graphs or those too large to represent in memory.
[src:ospf-routing/dijkstra-s-algorithm] Combinations of such techniques may be needed for optimal practical performance on specific problems.
[src:ospf-routing/dijkstra-s-algorithm] Two distance arrays are maintained: *df*[*v*] (distance from s to v) and *db*[*v*] (distance from v to t), initialized to ∞ except *df*[*s*] = 0 and *db*[*t*] = 0.
[src:ospf-routing/dijkstra-s-algorithm] Two priority queues *Qf* and *Qb* hold vertices not yet fully processed, and two sets *Sf* and *Sb* store vertices whose shortest-path distance is finalized in each direction.
[src:ospf-routing/dijkstra-s-algorithm] A variable μ stores the length of the best full s–t path found so far, initially ∞.
[src:ospf-routing/dijkstra-s-algorithm] and symmetrically for the backward search.
[src:ospf-routing/dijkstra-s-algorithm] A key feature is the stopping condition: once the sum of the current minimum priorities in both queues is at least μ, no yet-unsettled path can improve upon μ.
[src:ospf-routing/dijkstra-s-algorithm] At this point μ equals the true shortest-path distance δ(*s*,*t*), and the search terminates.
[src:ospf-routing/dijkstra-s-algorithm] This criterion avoids a common mistake of halting as soon as the two frontiers touch, which may overlook a shorter alternative crossing elsewhere.
[src:ospf-routing/dijkstra-s-algorithm] Because each search only needs to explore roughly half of the search space in typical graphs, the bidirectional method often visits far fewer vertices and relaxes far fewer edges than one-directional Dijkstra on single-pair queries.
[src:ospf-routing/dijkstra-s-algorithm] In road-network–like graphs the savings can be dramatic, sometimes reducing the explored region from an exponential-size ball to two smaller half-balls.
[src:ospf-routing/dijkstra-s-algorithm] The method is widely used in point-to-point routing for maps and navigation software and serves as a base for many speed-up techniques such as the ALT, contraction hierarchies, and reach-based routing.
[src:ospf-routing/dijkstra-s-algorithm] If the actual shortest path (not just its distance) is desired, predecessor pointers can be stored in both searches.
[src:ospf-routing/dijkstra-s-algorithm] When μ is updated through some crossing vertex x, the algorithm records this meeting point and reconstructs the final route as the forward path from s to x concatenated with the backward path from x to t.
[src:ospf-routing/dijkstra-s-algorithm] Theoretical research shows that an optimized bidirectional approach can be instance-optimal, meaning no correct algorithm can asymptotically relax fewer edges on the same graph instance.
[src:ospf-routing/dijkstra-s-algorithm] Although Dijkstra's algorithm is optimal for graphs with non-negative edge weights, its practical runtime depends on both data structures and graph properties.
[src:ospf-routing/dijkstra-s-algorithm] Using a binary heap results in a running time of O((V+E)logV).
[src:ospf-routing/dijkstra-s-algorithm] Alternatives such as Fibonacci heaps provide better theoretical bounds but often perform worse in real applications because of large constant factors.
[src:ospf-routing/dijkstra-s-algorithm] Graph structure also plays a major role.
[src:ospf-routing/dijkstra-s-algorithm] Sparse networks, such as road maps, allow Dijkstra's algorithm to operate efficiently since most vertices have low degree.
[src:ospf-routing/dijkstra-s-algorithm] Dense graphs increase relaxations and slow down the process.
[src:ospf-routing/dijkstra-s-algorithm] Because of this, modern routing systems often use Dijkstra's algorithm together with preprocessing methods such as A* search, landmark heuristics, or contraction hierarchies, which significantly reduce the search space.
[src:ospf-routing/dijkstra-s-algorithm] Memory locality is another important factor.
[src:ospf-routing/dijkstra-s-algorithm] Cache-optimized priority queues and adjacency layouts can reduce latency for large graphs that exceed CPU cache limitations.
[src:ospf-routing/dijkstra-s-algorithm] Because of these considerations, most real-world systems use specialized Dijkstra variants tuned for specific graph families and hardware constraints.
[src:ospf-routing/dijkstra-s-algorithm] As well as simply computing distances and paths, Dijkstra's algorithm can be used to sort vertices by their distances from a given starting vertex.
[src:ospf-routing/dijkstra-s-algorithm] To achieve this, they use a comparison-based heap whose cost of returning/removing the minimum element from the heap is logarithmic in the number of elements inserted after it rather than in the number of elements in the heap.
[src:ospf-routing/dijkstra-s-algorithm] When arc weights are small integers (bounded by a parameter C ), specialized queues can be used for increased speed.
[src:ospf-routing/dijkstra-s-algorithm] The first algorithm of this type was Dial's algorithm for graphs with positive integer edge weights, which uses a bucket queue to obtain a running time $O(|E|+|V|C)$ .
[src:ospf-routing/dijkstra-s-algorithm] The use of a Van Emde Boas tree as the priority queue brings the complexity to $O(|E|+|V|\log C/\log \log |V|C)$ .
[src:ospf-routing/dijkstra-s-algorithm] Another interesting variant based on a combination of a new radix heap and the well-known Fibonacci heap runs in time $O(|E|+|V|{\sqrt {\log C}})$ .
[src:ospf-routing/dijkstra-s-algorithm] Dijkstra's original algorithm can be extended with modifications.
[src:ospf-routing/dijkstra-s-algorithm] For example, sometimes it is desirable to present solutions which are less than mathematically optimal.
[src:ospf-routing/dijkstra-s-algorithm] To obtain a ranked list of less-than-optimal solutions, the optimal solution is first calculated.
[src:ospf-routing/dijkstra-s-algorithm] A single edge appearing in the optimal solution is removed from the graph, and the optimum solution to this new graph is calculated.
[src:ospf-routing/dijkstra-s-algorithm] Each edge of the original solution is suppressed in turn and a new shortest-path calculated.
[src:ospf-routing/dijkstra-s-algorithm] The secondary solutions are then ranked and presented after the first optimal solution.
[src:ospf-routing/dijkstra-s-algorithm] Dijkstra's algorithm is usually the working principle behind link-state routing protocols.
[src:ospf-routing/dijkstra-s-algorithm] Unlike Dijkstra's algorithm, the Bellman–Ford algorithm can be used on graphs with negative edge weights, as long as the graph contains no negative cycle reachable from the source vertex *s*.
[src:ospf-routing/dijkstra-s-algorithm] The presence of such cycles means that no shortest path can be found, since the label becomes lower each time the cycle is traversed.
[src:ospf-routing/dijkstra-s-algorithm] (This statement assumes that a "path" is allowed to repeat vertices.
[src:ospf-routing/dijkstra-s-algorithm] In graph theory that is normally not allowed.
[src:ospf-routing/dijkstra-s-algorithm] In theoretical computer science it often is allowed.) It is possible to adapt Dijkstra's algorithm to handle negative weights by combining it with the Bellman-Ford algorithm (to remove negative edges and detect negative cycles): Johnson's algorithm.
[src:ospf-routing/dijkstra-s-algorithm] The A* algorithm is a generalization of Dijkstra's algorithm that reduces the size of the subgraph that must be explored, if additional information is available that provides a lower bound on the distance to the target.
[src:ospf-routing/dijkstra-s-algorithm] The process that underlies Dijkstra's algorithm is similar to the greedy process used in Prim's algorithm.
[src:ospf-routing/dijkstra-s-algorithm] Prim's purpose is to find a minimum spanning tree that connects all nodes in the graph; Dijkstra is concerned with only two nodes.
[src:ospf-routing/dijkstra-s-algorithm] Prim's does not evaluate the total weight of the path from the starting node, only the individual edges.
[src:ospf-routing/dijkstra-s-algorithm] Breadth-first search can be viewed as a special-case of Dijkstra's algorithm on unweighted graphs, where the priority queue degenerates into a FIFO queue.
[src:ospf-routing/dijkstra-s-algorithm] The fast marching method can be viewed as a continuous version of Dijkstra's algorithm which computes the geodesic distance on a triangle mesh.
[src:ospf-routing/dijkstra-s-algorithm] From a dynamic programming point of view, Dijkstra's algorithm is a successive approximation scheme that solves the dynamic programming functional equation for the shortest path problem by the **Reaching** method.
[src:ospf-routing/dijkstra-s-algorithm] is a paraphrasing of Bellman's principle of optimality in the context of the shortest path problem.
[src:ospf-routing/interior-gateway-protocol] An **interior gateway protocol** (**IGP**) or **interior routing protocol** is a type of routing protocol used for exchanging routing table information between gateways (commonly routers) *within* an autonomous system (for example, a system of corporate local area networks).
[src:ospf-routing/interior-gateway-protocol] This routing information can then be used to route network-layer protocols like IP.
[src:ospf-routing/interior-gateway-protocol] Interior gateway protocols can be divided into two categories: distance-vector routing protocols and link-state routing protocols.
[src:ospf-routing/interior-gateway-protocol] Specific examples of IGPs include Open Shortest Path First (OSPF), Routing Information Protocol (RIP), Intermediate System to Intermediate System (IS-IS) and Enhanced Interior Gateway Routing Protocol (EIGRP).
[src:ospf-routing/interior-gateway-protocol] By contrast, exterior gateway protocols are used to exchange routing information *between* autonomous systems and rely on IGPs to resolve routes within an autonomous system.
[src:ospf-routing/interior-gateway-protocol] Advanced distance vector routing protocols have both the features of distance vector routing protocols and link-state routing protocols.
[src:ospf-routing/interior-gateway-protocol] One example is Enhanced Interior Gateway Routing Protocol (EIGRP).
[src:ospf-routing/link-state-routing-protocol] The link-state protocol is performed by every *switching node* in the network (i.e., nodes which are prepared to forward packets; in the Internet, these are called routers).
[src:ospf-routing/link-state-routing-protocol] The basic concept of link-state routing is that every node constructs a *map* of the connectivity to the network in the form of a graph, showing which nodes are connected to which other nodes.
[src:ospf-routing/link-state-routing-protocol] Each node then independently calculates the next best logical *path* from it to every possible destination in the network.
[src:ospf-routing/link-state-routing-protocol] Each collection of best paths will then form each node's routing table.
[src:ospf-routing/link-state-routing-protocol] This contrasts with distance-vector routing protocols, which work by having each node share its routing table with its neighbors.
[src:ospf-routing/link-state-routing-protocol] In a link-state protocol, the only information passed between nodes is *connectivity related*.
[src:ospf-routing/link-state-routing-protocol] In link-state routing protocols, each router possesses information about the complete network topology.
[src:ospf-routing/link-state-routing-protocol] Each router then independently calculates the best next hop from it for every possible destination in the network using local information of the topology.
[src:ospf-routing/link-state-routing-protocol] The collection of best next hops forms the routing table.
[src:ospf-routing/link-state-routing-protocol] This contrasts with distance-vector routing protocols, which work by having each node share its routing table with its neighbours.
[src:ospf-routing/link-state-routing-protocol] In a link-state protocol, the only information passed between the nodes is the information used to construct the connectivity maps.
[src:ospf-routing/link-state-routing-protocol] What is believed to be the first adaptive routing network of computers, using link-state routing, was designed and implemented during 1976–1977 by a team from Plessey Radar led by Bernard J Harris; the project was for "Wavell" – a system of computer command and control for the British Army.
[src:ospf-routing/link-state-routing-protocol] The first link-state routing concept was published in 1979 by John M.
[src:ospf-routing/link-state-routing-protocol] McQuillan (then at Bolt, Beranek and Newman) as a mechanism that would calculate routes more quickly when network conditions changed and thus lead to more stable routing.
[src:ospf-routing/link-state-routing-protocol] The technique was later adapted for use in the contemporary link-state routing protocols IS-IS and OSPF.
[src:ospf-routing/link-state-routing-protocol] Cisco literature refers to Enhanced Interior Gateway Routing Protocol (EIGRP) as a "hybrid" protocol, despite the fact it distributes routing tables instead of topology maps.
[src:ospf-routing/link-state-routing-protocol] However, it does synchronize routing tables at start-up as OSPF does and sends specific updates only when topology changes occur.
[src:ospf-routing/link-state-routing-protocol] In 2004, Radia Perlman proposed using link-state routing for layer 2 frame forwarding with devices called routing bridges, or Rbridges.
[src:ospf-routing/link-state-routing-protocol] The Internet Engineering Task Force has standardized the Transparent Interconnection of Lots of Links (TRILL) protocol to accomplish this.
[src:ospf-routing/link-state-routing-protocol] More recently, this hierarchical technique was applied to wireless mesh networks using the Optimized Link State Routing Protocol (OLSR).
[src:ospf-routing/link-state-routing-protocol] Where a connection can have varying quality, the quality of a connection can be used to select better connections.
[src:ospf-routing/link-state-routing-protocol] This is used in some ad hoc routing protocols that use radio frequency transmission.
[src:ospf-routing/link-state-routing-protocol] The first main stage in the link-state algorithm is to give a map of the network to every node.
[src:ospf-routing/link-state-routing-protocol] This is done with several subsidiary steps.
[src:ospf-routing/link-state-routing-protocol] First, each node needs to determine what other ports it is connected to over fully working links; it does this using *reachability protocol* that it runs periodically and separately with each of its directly connected neighbours.
[src:ospf-routing/link-state-routing-protocol] This message is sent to all the nodes on a network.
[src:ospf-routing/link-state-routing-protocol] As a necessary precursor, each node in the network remembers, for every one of *its* neighbors, the sequence number of the last link-state message which it received from that node.
[src:ospf-routing/link-state-routing-protocol] This procedure rapidly gets a copy of the latest version of each node's link-state advertisement to every node in the network.
[src:ospf-routing/link-state-routing-protocol] The complete set produces the graph for the map of the network.
[src:ospf-routing/link-state-routing-protocol] The link-state message giving information about the neighbors is recomputed and then flooded throughout the network whenever there is a change in the connectivity between the node and its neighbors, e.g., when a link fails.
[src:ospf-routing/link-state-routing-protocol] The second main stage in the link-state algorithm is to produce routing tables by inspecting the maps.
[src:ospf-routing/link-state-routing-protocol] Each node independently runs an algorithm over the map to determine the shortest path from itself to every other node in the network; generally, some variant of Dijkstra's algorithm is used.
[src:ospf-routing/link-state-routing-protocol] A node maintains two data structures: a Tree data structure tree containing nodes which are "done", and a list of *candidates*.
[src:ospf-routing/link-state-routing-protocol] The algorithm starts with both structures empty; it then adds to the first one the node itself.
[src:ospf-routing/link-state-routing-protocol] The two steps are repeated as long as there are any nodes left in the candidate list.
[src:ospf-routing/link-state-routing-protocol] (When there are none, all the nodes in the network will have been added to the tree.) This procedure ends with the tree containing all the nodes in the network.
[src:ospf-routing/link-state-routing-protocol] For any given destination node, the best path for that destination is the node which is the first step from the root node, down the branch in the shortest-path tree which leads toward the desired destination node.
[src:ospf-routing/link-state-routing-protocol] Whenever a change in the connectivity map happens, it is necessary to recompute the shortest-path tree and then recreate the routing table.
[src:ospf-routing/link-state-routing-protocol] BBN Technologies discovered how to compute only that part of the tree which could have been affected by a given change in the map.
[src:ospf-routing/link-state-routing-protocol] In some cases, it is reasonable to reduce the number of nodes that generate LSA messages.
[src:ospf-routing/link-state-routing-protocol] For this reason, a topology reduction strategy can be applied, in which only a subset of the network nodes generate LSA messages.
[src:ospf-routing/link-state-routing-protocol] Two widely studied approaches for topology reduction are multipoint relays that are at the base of the Optimized Link State Routing Protocol (OLSR) but have also been proposed for OSPF and connected dominating sets that were again proposed for OSPF.
[src:ospf-routing/link-state-routing-protocol] With Fisheye State Routing (FSR), the LSA are sent with different time-to-live values to restrict their diffusion and limit the overhead due to control messages.
[src:ospf-routing/link-state-routing-protocol] The same concept is used also in the Hazy Sighted Link State Routing Protocol.
[src:ospf-routing/link-state-routing-protocol] If all the nodes are not working from exactly the same map, *routing loops* can form.
[src:ospf-routing/link-state-routing-protocol] These are situations in which, in the simplest form, two neighboring nodes each think the other is the best path to a given destination.
[src:ospf-routing/link-state-routing-protocol] Any packet headed to that destination arriving at either node will loop between the two, hence the name.
[src:ospf-routing/link-state-routing-protocol] Routing loops involving more than two nodes are also possible.
[src:ospf-routing/link-state-routing-protocol] This can occur since each node computes its shortest-path tree and its routing table without interacting in any way with any other nodes.
[src:ospf-routing/link-state-routing-protocol] If two nodes start with different maps, it is possible to have scenarios in which routing loops are created.
[src:ospf-routing/link-state-routing-protocol] In certain circumstances, differential loops may be enabled within a multi-cloud environment.
[src:ospf-routing/link-state-routing-protocol] Variable access nodes across the interface protocol may also bypass the simultaneous access node problem.
[src:ospf-routing/link-state-routing-protocol] The Optimized Link State Routing Protocol (OLSR) is a link-state routing protocol optimized for mobile ad hoc networks (which can also be used on other wireless ad hoc networks).
[src:ospf-routing/link-state-routing-protocol] OLSR is proactive and uses hello and topology control messages to disseminate link-state information into the mobile ad hoc network.
[src:ospf-routing/link-state-routing-protocol] Using hello messages, each node discovers two-hop neighbor information and elects a set of *multipoint relays* (MPRs).
[src:ospf-routing/link-state-routing-protocol] MPRs make OLSR distinct from other link-state routing protocols.
[src:ospf-routing/link-state-routing-protocol] Individual nodes use the topology information to compute next-hop paths regarding all nodes in the network using shortest-hop forwarding paths.
[src:ospf-routing/open-shortest-path-first] OSPF gathers link state information from available routers and constructs a topology map of the network.
[src:ospf-routing/open-shortest-path-first] The topology is presented as a routing table to the internet layer for routing packets by their destination IP address.
[src:ospf-routing/open-shortest-path-first] OSPF supports Internet Protocol version 4 (IPv4) and Internet Protocol version 6 (IPv6) networks and is widely used in large enterprise networks.
[src:ospf-routing/open-shortest-path-first] IS-IS, another LSR-based protocol, is more common in large service provider networks.
[src:ospf-routing/open-shortest-path-first] Originally designed in the 1980s, OSPF version 2 is defined in RFC 2328 (1998).
[src:ospf-routing/open-shortest-path-first] The updates for IPv6 are specified as OSPF version 3 in RFC 5340 (2008).
[src:ospf-routing/open-shortest-path-first] OSPF supports the Classless Inter-Domain Routing (CIDR) addressing model.
[src:ospf-routing/open-shortest-path-first] OSPF is an interior gateway protocol (IGP) for routing Internet Protocol (IP) packets within a single routing domain, such as an autonomous system.
[src:ospf-routing/open-shortest-path-first] It gathers link state information from available routers and constructs a topology map of the network.
[src:ospf-routing/open-shortest-path-first] The topology is presented as a routing table to the internet layer, which routes packets based solely on their destination IP address.
[src:ospf-routing/open-shortest-path-first] OSPF detects changes in the topology, such as link failures, and converges on a new loop-free routing structure within seconds.
[src:ospf-routing/open-shortest-path-first] It computes the shortest-path tree for each route using a method based on Dijkstra's algorithm.
[src:ospf-routing/open-shortest-path-first] The OSPF routing policies for constructing a route table are governed by link metrics associated with each routing interface.
[src:ospf-routing/open-shortest-path-first] Cost factors may be the distance of a router (round-trip time), data throughput of a link, or link availability and reliability, expressed as simple unitless numbers.
[src:ospf-routing/open-shortest-path-first] This provides a dynamic process of traffic load balancing between routes of equal cost.
[src:ospf-routing/open-shortest-path-first] OSPF divides the network into routing *areas* to simplify administration and optimize traffic and resource utilization.
[src:ospf-routing/open-shortest-path-first] Areas are identified by 32-bit numbers, expressed either simply in decimal or often in the same octet-based dot-decimal notation used for IPv4 addresses.
[src:ospf-routing/open-shortest-path-first] By convention, area 0 (zero), or 0.0.0.0, represents the *core* or *backbone* area of an OSPF network.
[src:ospf-routing/open-shortest-path-first] While the identifications of other areas may be chosen at will, administrators often select the IP address of a main router in an area as the area identifier.
[src:ospf-routing/open-shortest-path-first] Each additional area must have a connection to the OSPF backbone area.
[src:ospf-routing/open-shortest-path-first] Such connections are maintained by an interconnecting router, known as an area border router (ABR).
[src:ospf-routing/open-shortest-path-first] An ABR maintains separate link-state databases for each area it serves and maintains summarized routes for all areas in the network.
[src:ospf-routing/open-shortest-path-first] OSPF runs over IPv4 and IPv6, but does not use a transport protocol such as UDP or TCP.
[src:ospf-routing/open-shortest-path-first] It encapsulates its data directly in IP packets with protocol number 89.
[src:ospf-routing/open-shortest-path-first] This is in contrast to other routing protocols, such as the Routing Information Protocol (RIP) and the Border Gateway Protocol (BGP).
[src:ospf-routing/open-shortest-path-first] OSPF implements its own transport error detection and correction functions.
[src:ospf-routing/open-shortest-path-first] OSPF also uses multicast addressing for distributing route information within a broadcast domain.
[src:ospf-routing/open-shortest-path-first] It reserves the multicast addresses *224.0.0.5* (IPv4) and *ff02::5* (IPv6) for all SPF/link state routers (AllSPFRouters) and *224.0.0.6* (IPv4) and *ff02::6* (IPv6) for all Designated Routers (AllDRouters).
[src:ospf-routing/open-shortest-path-first] For non-broadcast networks, special provisions for configuration facilitate neighbor discovery.
[src:ospf-routing/open-shortest-path-first] OSPF multicast IP packets never traverse IP routers, they never travel more than one hop.
[src:ospf-routing/open-shortest-path-first] The protocol may therefore be considered a link-layer protocol, but is often also attributed to the application layer in the TCP/IP model.
[src:ospf-routing/open-shortest-path-first] It has a virtual link feature that can be used to create an adjacency tunnel across multiple hops.
[src:ospf-routing/open-shortest-path-first] OSPF over IPv4 can operate securely between routers, optionally using a variety of authentication methods to allow only trusted routers to participate in routing.
[src:ospf-routing/open-shortest-path-first] OSPFv3 (IPv6) relies on standard IPv6 protocol security (IPsec), and has no internal authentication methods.
[src:ospf-routing/open-shortest-path-first] For routing IP multicast traffic, OSPF supports the Multicast Open Shortest Path First (MOSPF) protocol.
[src:ospf-routing/open-shortest-path-first] Cisco does not include MOSPF in their OSPF implementations.
[src:ospf-routing/open-shortest-path-first] Protocol Independent Multicast (PIM) in conjunction with OSPF or other IGPs, is widely deployed.
[src:ospf-routing/open-shortest-path-first] OSPF version 3 introduces modifications to the IPv4 implementation of the protocol.
[src:ospf-routing/open-shortest-path-first] Except for virtual links, all neighbor exchanges use IPv6 link-local addressing exclusively.
[src:ospf-routing/open-shortest-path-first] The IPv6 protocol runs per link, rather than based on the subnet.
[src:ospf-routing/open-shortest-path-first] All IP prefix information has been removed from the link-state advertisements and from the *hello* discovery packet, making OSPFv3 essentially protocol-independent.
[src:ospf-routing/open-shortest-path-first] Despite the expanded IP addressing to 128 bits in IPv6, area and router Identifications are still based on 32-bit numbers.
[src:ospf-routing/open-shortest-path-first] OSPF supports complex networks with multiple routers, including backup routers, to balance traffic load on multiple links to other subnets.
[src:ospf-routing/open-shortest-path-first] Neighboring routers in the same broadcast domain or at each end of a point-to-point link communicate with each other via the OSPF protocol.
[src:ospf-routing/open-shortest-path-first] Routers form *adjacencies* when they have detected each other.
[src:ospf-routing/open-shortest-path-first] This detection is initiated when a router identifies itself in a *hello* protocol packet.
[src:ospf-routing/open-shortest-path-first] Upon acknowledgment, this establishes a *two-way state* and the most basic relationship.
[src:ospf-routing/open-shortest-path-first] The routers in an Ethernet or Frame Relay network select a *designated router* (DR) and a *backup designated router* (BDR), which act as a hub to reduce traffic between routers.
[src:ospf-routing/open-shortest-path-first] OSPF uses both unicast and multicast transmission modes to send "hello" packets and link-state updates.
[src:ospf-routing/open-shortest-path-first] As a link-state routing protocol, OSPF establishes and maintains neighbor relationships for exchanging routing updates with other routers.
[src:ospf-routing/open-shortest-path-first] The neighbor relationship table is called an *adjacency database*.
[src:ospf-routing/open-shortest-path-first] Two OSPF routers are neighbors if they are members of the same subnet and share the same area ID, subnet mask, timers and authentication.
[src:ospf-routing/open-shortest-path-first] In essence, OSPF neighborship is a relationship between two routers that allows them to see and understand each other but nothing more.
[src:ospf-routing/open-shortest-path-first] OSPF neighbors do not exchange any routing information – the only packets they exchange are hello packets.
[src:ospf-routing/open-shortest-path-first] OSPF adjacencies are formed between selected neighbors and allow them to exchange routing information.
[src:ospf-routing/open-shortest-path-first] Two routers must first be neighbors, and only then can they become adjacent.
[src:ospf-routing/open-shortest-path-first] Two routers become adjacent if at least one of them is designated router or backup designated router (on multiaccess-type networks), or they are interconnected by a point-to-point or point-to-multipoint network type.
[src:ospf-routing/open-shortest-path-first] For forming a neighbor relationship between the interfaces, the relationship must be in the same OSPF area.
[src:ospf-routing/open-shortest-path-first] While an interface may be configured to belong to multiple areas, this is generally not practiced.
[src:ospf-routing/open-shortest-path-first] When configured in a second area, an interface must be configured as a secondary interface.
[src:ospf-routing/open-shortest-path-first] Virtual link over Virtual links, tunneling and sham links, are a form of connections that goes over the routing engine, and is not a direct connection to the remote host.
[src:ospf-routing/open-shortest-path-first] Each OSPF router within a network communicates with other neighboring routers on each connecting interface to establish the states of all adjacencies.
[src:ospf-routing/open-shortest-path-first] Every such communication sequence is a separate *conversation* identified by the pair of router IDs of the communicating neighbors.
[src:ospf-routing/open-shortest-path-first] RFC 2328 specifies the protocol for initiating these conversations (*Hello Protocol*) and for establishing full adjacencies (*database description packets*, *link-state request packets*).
[src:ospf-routing/open-shortest-path-first] Attempt: The *attempt* state is similar to the *down* state, except that a router is in the process of efforts to establish a conversation with another router, but is only used on non-broadcast multiple-access networks (NBMAs).
[src:ospf-routing/open-shortest-path-first] Init: The *init* state indicates that a hello packet has been received from a neighbor, but the router has not established a two-way conversation.
[src:ospf-routing/open-shortest-path-first] Two-way: The *two-way* state indicates the establishment of a bidirectional conversation between two routers.
[src:ospf-routing/open-shortest-path-first] This state immediately precedes the establishment of adjacency.
[src:ospf-routing/open-shortest-path-first] This is the lowest state of a router that may be considered as a DR.
[src:ospf-routing/open-shortest-path-first] Exchange: In the *exchange* state, a router is sending its link-state database information to the adjacent neighbor.
[src:ospf-routing/open-shortest-path-first] At this state, a router can exchange all OSPF routing protocol packets.
[src:ospf-routing/open-shortest-path-first] Loading: In the *loading* state, a router requests the most recent link-state advertisements (LSAs) from its neighbor discovered in the previous state.
[src:ospf-routing/open-shortest-path-first] Full: The *full* state concludes the conversation when the routers are fully adjacent, and the state appears in all router- and network-LSAs.
[src:ospf-routing/open-shortest-path-first] The link-state databases of the neighbors are fully synchronized.
[src:ospf-routing/open-shortest-path-first] In broadcast multiple-access networks, neighbor adjacency is formed dynamically using multicast hello packets to *224.0.0.5*.
[src:ospf-routing/open-shortest-path-first] A network where OSPF advertises the network, but OSPF will not start neighbor adjacency.
[src:ospf-routing/open-shortest-path-first] In a non-broadcast multiple-access (NBMA) network, a neighbor adjacency is formed by sending unicast packets to another router.
[src:ospf-routing/open-shortest-path-first] A non-broadcast network can have more than two routers, but broadcast is not supported.
[src:ospf-routing/open-shortest-path-first] A network is divided into OSPF *areas* that are logical groupings of contiguous hosts and networks.
[src:ospf-routing/open-shortest-path-first] An area includes its connecting router, having an interface for each connected network link.
[src:ospf-routing/open-shortest-path-first] Each router maintains a separate link-state database for the area whose information may be summarized towards the rest of the network by the connecting router.
[src:ospf-routing/open-shortest-path-first] Thus, the topology of an area is unknown outside the area.
[src:ospf-routing/open-shortest-path-first] This reduces the routing traffic between parts of an autonomous system.
[src:ospf-routing/open-shortest-path-first] Though OSPF can handle thousands of routers, there is a concern reaching the capacity of the forwarding information base (FIB) table when the network contains lots of routes and lower-end devices.
[src:ospf-routing/open-shortest-path-first] Modern low-end routers have a full gigabyte of RAM, which allows them to handle many routers in an area 0.
[src:ospf-routing/open-shortest-path-first] Many resources refer to OSPF guides from over 20 years ago, where it was impressive to have 64 MB of RAM.
[src:ospf-routing/open-shortest-path-first] Areas are uniquely identified with 32-bit numbers.
[src:ospf-routing/open-shortest-path-first] The area identifiers are commonly written in the dot-decimal notation, familiar from IPv4 addressing.
[src:ospf-routing/open-shortest-path-first] However, they are not IP addresses and may duplicate, without conflict, any IPv4 address.
[src:ospf-routing/open-shortest-path-first] The area identifiers for IPv6 implementations (OSPFv3) also use 32-bit identifiers written in the same notation.
[src:ospf-routing/open-shortest-path-first] When dotted formatting is omitted, most implementations expand area *1* to the area identifier *0.0.0.1*, but some have been known to expand it as *1.0.0.0*.
[src:ospf-routing/open-shortest-path-first] Several vendors (Cisco, Allied Telesis, Juniper, Alcatel-Lucent, Huawei, Quagga), implement *totally stubby* and *NSSA totally stubby area* for stub and not-so-stubby areas.
[src:ospf-routing/open-shortest-path-first] Although not covered by RFC standards, they are considered by many to be standard features in OSPF implementations.
[src:ospf-routing/open-shortest-path-first] The backbone area (also known as *area 0* or *area 0.0.0.0*) forms the core of an OSPF network.
[src:ospf-routing/open-shortest-path-first] All other areas are connected to it, either directly or through other routers.
[src:ospf-routing/open-shortest-path-first] OSPF requires this to prevent routing loops.
[src:ospf-routing/open-shortest-path-first] Inter-area routing happens via routers connected to the backbone area and to their own associated areas.
[src:ospf-routing/open-shortest-path-first] It is the logical and physical structure for the 'OSPF domain' and is attached to all nonzero areas in the OSPF domain.
[src:ospf-routing/open-shortest-path-first] In OSPF the term *autonomous system boundary router* (ASBR) is historic, in the sense that many OSPF domains can coexist in the same Internet-visible autonomous system, RFC 1996.
[src:ospf-routing/open-shortest-path-first] All OSPF areas must connect to the backbone area.
[src:ospf-routing/open-shortest-path-first] This connection, however, can be through a virtual link.
[src:ospf-routing/open-shortest-path-first] For example, assume area 0.0.0.1 has a physical connection to area 0.0.0.0.
[src:ospf-routing/open-shortest-path-first] Further assume that area 0.0.0.2 has no direct connection to the backbone, but this area does have a connection to area 0.0.0.1.
[src:ospf-routing/open-shortest-path-first] Area 0.0.0.2 can use a virtual link through the *transit area* 0.0.0.1 to reach the backbone.
[src:ospf-routing/open-shortest-path-first] To be a transit area, an area has to have the transit attribute, so it cannot be stubby in any way.
[src:ospf-routing/open-shortest-path-first] A regular area is just a non-backbone (nonzero) area without a specific feature, generating and receiving summary and external LSAs.
[src:ospf-routing/open-shortest-path-first] The backbone area is a special type of such area.
[src:ospf-routing/open-shortest-path-first] A stub area is an area that does not receive route advertisements external to the AS, and routing from within the area is based entirely on a default route.
[src:ospf-routing/open-shortest-path-first] An ABR deletes type 4 and 5 LSAs from internal routers, sends them a default route of 0.0.0.0, and turns itself into a default gateway.
[src:ospf-routing/open-shortest-path-first] This reduces LSDB and routing table size for internal routers.
[src:ospf-routing/open-shortest-path-first] Modifications to the basic concept of stub area have been implemented by systems vendors, such as the *totally stubby area* (TSA) and the *not-so-stubby area* (NSSA), both extensions in Cisco Systems routing equipment.
[src:ospf-routing/open-shortest-path-first] A *totally stubby area* is similar to a stub area.
[src:ospf-routing/open-shortest-path-first] However, this area does not allow *summary* routes in addition to not having *external* routes; that is, *inter-area* (IA) routes are not summarized into totally stubby areas.
[src:ospf-routing/open-shortest-path-first] The only way for traffic to get routed outside the area is a default route, which is the only Type-3 LSA advertised into the area.
[src:ospf-routing/open-shortest-path-first] When there is only one route out of the area, fewer routing decisions have to be made by the route processor, which lowers system resource utilization.
[src:ospf-routing/open-shortest-path-first] Occasionally, it is said that a TSA can have only one ABR.
[src:ospf-routing/open-shortest-path-first] A *not-so-stubby area* (NSSA) is a type of stub area that can import autonomous system external routes and send them to other areas, but still cannot receive AS-external routes from other areas.
[src:ospf-routing/open-shortest-path-first] NSSA is an extension of the stub area feature that allows the injection of external routes in a limited fashion into the stub area.
[src:ospf-routing/open-shortest-path-first] A case study simulates an NSSA getting around the stub-area problem of not being able to import external addresses.
[src:ospf-routing/open-shortest-path-first] It visualizes the following activities: the ASBR imports external addresses with a type 7 LSA, the ABR converts a type 7 LSA to type 5 and floods it to other areas, the ABR acts as an ASBR for other areas.
[src:ospf-routing/open-shortest-path-first] The ASBRs do not take type 5 LSAs and then convert to type 7 LSAs for the area.
[src:ospf-routing/open-shortest-path-first] An addition to the standard functionality of an NSSA, the *totally stubby NSSA* is an NSSA that takes on the attributes of a TSA, meaning that type 3 and 4 summary routes are not flooded into this type of area.
[src:ospf-routing/open-shortest-path-first] Redistribution into an NSSA area creates a special type of LSA known as type 7, which can exist only in an NSSA area.
[src:ospf-routing/open-shortest-path-first] An NSSA ASBR generates this LSA, and an NSSA ABR router translates it into a type 5 LSA, which gets propagated into the OSPF domain.
[src:ospf-routing/open-shortest-path-first] A newly acquired subsidiary is one example of where it might be suitable for an area to be simultaneously not-so-stubby and totally stubby if the practical place to put an ASBR is on the edge of a totally stubby area.
[src:ospf-routing/open-shortest-path-first] In such a case, the ASBR does send externals into the totally stubby area, and they are available to OSPF speakers within that area.
[src:ospf-routing/open-shortest-path-first] In Cisco's implementation, the external routes can be summarized before injecting them into the totally stubby area.
[src:ospf-routing/open-shortest-path-first] In general, the ASBR should not advertise default into the TSA-NSSA, although this can work with extremely careful design and operation, for the limited special cases in which such an advertisement makes sense.
[src:ospf-routing/open-shortest-path-first] By declaring the totally stubby area as NSSA, no external routes from the backbone, except the default route, enter the area being discussed.
[src:ospf-routing/open-shortest-path-first] The externals do reach area 0.0.0.0 via the TSA-NSSA, but no routes other than the default route enter the TSA-NSSA.
[src:ospf-routing/open-shortest-path-first] Routers in the TSA-NSSA send all traffic to the ABR, except to routes advertised by the ASBR.
[src:ospf-routing/open-shortest-path-first] has all its interfaces belonging to the same area.
[src:ospf-routing/open-shortest-path-first] is a router that connects one or more areas to the main backbone network.
[src:ospf-routing/open-shortest-path-first] It is considered a member of all areas it is connected to.
[src:ospf-routing/open-shortest-path-first] of the link-state database in memory, one for each area to which that router is connected.
[src:ospf-routing/open-shortest-path-first] Backbone routers may also be area border routers, but do not have to be.
[src:ospf-routing/open-shortest-path-first] is a router that is connected by using more than one routing protocol and that exchanges routing information with routers autonomous systems.
[src:ospf-routing/open-shortest-path-first] received from other, external ASs throughout its own autonomous system.
[src:ospf-routing/open-shortest-path-first] An ASBR creates External LSAs for external addresses and floods them to all areas via ABR.
[src:ospf-routing/open-shortest-path-first] Routers in other areas use ABRs as next hops to access external addresses.
[src:ospf-routing/open-shortest-path-first] Then ABRs forward packets to the ASBR that announces the external addresses.
[src:ospf-routing/open-shortest-path-first] The router type is an attribute of an OSPF process.
[src:ospf-routing/open-shortest-path-first] A given physical router may have one or more OSPF processes.
[src:ospf-routing/open-shortest-path-first] For example, a router that is connected to more than one area, and which receives routes from a BGP process connected to another AS, is both an area border router and an autonomous system boundary router.
[src:ospf-routing/open-shortest-path-first] Each router has an identifier, customarily written in the dotted-decimal format (e.g., 1.2.3.4) of an IP address.
[src:ospf-routing/open-shortest-path-first] This identifier must be established in every OSPF instance.
[src:ospf-routing/open-shortest-path-first] If not explicitly configured, the highest logical IP address will be duplicated as the router identifier.
[src:ospf-routing/open-shortest-path-first] However, since the router identifier is not an IP address, it does not have to be a part of any routable subnet in the network, and often isn't to avoid confusion.
[src:ospf-routing/open-shortest-path-first] A system of *designated router* (DR) and *backup designated router* (BDR), is used to reduce network traffic by providing a source for routing updates.
[src:ospf-routing/open-shortest-path-first] The DR and BDR maintains a complete topology table of the network and sends the updates to the other routers via multicast.
[src:ospf-routing/open-shortest-path-first] All routers in a multi-access network segment will form a leader/follower relationship with the DR and BDR.
[src:ospf-routing/open-shortest-path-first] They will form adjacencies with the DR and BDR only.
[src:ospf-routing/open-shortest-path-first] Every time a router sends an update, it sends it to the DR and BDR on the multicast address *224.0.0.6*.
[src:ospf-routing/open-shortest-path-first] The DR will then send the update out to all other routers in the area, to the multicast address *224.0.0.5*.
[src:ospf-routing/open-shortest-path-first] This way all the routers do not have to constantly update each other, and can rather get all their updates from a single source.
[src:ospf-routing/open-shortest-path-first] The use of multicasting further reduces the network load.
[src:ospf-routing/open-shortest-path-first] DRs and BDRs are always setup/elected on OSPF broadcast networks.
[src:ospf-routing/open-shortest-path-first] DR's can also be elected on NBMA (Non-Broadcast Multi-Access) networks such as Frame Relay or ATM.
[src:ospf-routing/open-shortest-path-first] DRs or BDRs are not elected on point-to-point links (such as a point-to-point WAN connection) because the two routers on either side of the link must become fully adjacent and the bandwidth between them cannot be further optimized.
[src:ospf-routing/open-shortest-path-first] DR and non-DR routers evolve from 2-way to full adjacency relationships by exchanging DD, Request, and Update.
[src:ospf-routing/open-shortest-path-first] A *designated router* (DR) is the router interface elected among all routers on a particular multiaccess network segment, generally assumed to be broadcast multiaccess.
[src:ospf-routing/open-shortest-path-first] Special techniques, often vendor-dependent, may be needed to support the DR function on non-broadcast multiaccess (NBMA) media.
[src:ospf-routing/open-shortest-path-first] It is usually wise to configure the individual virtual circuits of an NBMA subnet as individual point-to-point lines; the techniques used are implementation-dependent.
[src:ospf-routing/open-shortest-path-first] A *backup designated router* (BDR) is a router that becomes the designated router if the current designated router has a problem or fails.
[src:ospf-routing/open-shortest-path-first] The BDR is the OSPF router with the second-highest priority at the time of the last election.
[src:ospf-routing/open-shortest-path-first] A given router can have some interfaces that are designated (DR) and others that are backup designated (BDR), and others that are non-designated.
[src:ospf-routing/open-shortest-path-first] If no router is a DR or a BDR on a given subnet, the BDR is first elected, and then a second election is held for the DR.
[src:ospf-routing/open-shortest-path-first] A router that has not been selected to be *designated router* (DR) or *backup designated router* (BDR).
[src:ospf-routing/open-shortest-path-first] The router forms an adjacency to both the *designated router* (DR) and the *backup designated router* (BDR).
[src:ospf-routing/open-shortest-path-first] For other non (B)DR, the adjacency stops at *2-ways* State.
[src:ospf-routing/open-shortest-path-first] Unlike other routing protocols, OSPF does not carry data via a transport protocol, such as the User Datagram Protocol (UDP) or the Transmission Control Protocol (TCP).
[src:ospf-routing/open-shortest-path-first] Instead, OSPF forms IP datagrams directly, packaging them using protocol number 89 for the IP Protocol field.
[src:ospf-routing/open-shortest-path-first] OSPF defines five different message types, for various types of communication.
[src:ospf-routing/open-shortest-path-first] OSPF's Hello messages are used as a form of greeting, to allow a router to discover other adjacent routers on its local links and networks.
[src:ospf-routing/open-shortest-path-first] The messages establish relationships between neighboring devices (called adjacencies) and communicate key parameters about how OSPF is to be used in the autonomous system or area.
[src:ospf-routing/open-shortest-path-first] During normal operation, routers send hello messages to their neighbors at regular intervals (the *hello interval*); if a router stops receiving hello messages from a neighbor, after a set period (the *dead interval*) the router will assume the neighbor has gone down.
[src:ospf-routing/open-shortest-path-first] messages are used by one router to request updated information about a portion of the LSDB from another router.
[src:ospf-routing/open-shortest-path-first] The message specifies the link(s) for which the requesting device wants more current information.
[src:ospf-routing/open-shortest-path-first] messages contain updated information about the state of certain links on the LSDB.
[src:ospf-routing/open-shortest-path-first] They are sent in response to a link state request message, and also broadcast or multicast by routers on a regular basis.
[src:ospf-routing/open-shortest-path-first] Their contents are used to update the information in the LSDBs of routers that receive them.
[src:ospf-routing/open-shortest-path-first] messages provide reliability to the link-state exchange process, by explicitly acknowledging receipt of a Link State Update message.
[src:ospf-routing/open-shortest-path-first] OSPF uses *path cost* as its basic routing metric, which was defined by the standard not to equate to any standard value such as speed, so the network designer could pick a metric important to the design.
[src:ospf-routing/open-shortest-path-first] In practice, it is determined by comparing the speed of the interface to a reference-bandwidth for the OSPF process.
[src:ospf-routing/open-shortest-path-first] The cost is determined by dividing the reference bandwidth by the interface speed (although the cost for any interface can be manually overridden).
[src:ospf-routing/open-shortest-path-first] Here is an example table that shows the routing metric or 'cost calculation' on an interface.
[src:ospf-routing/open-shortest-path-first] If a layer 2 switch is between the two devices running OSPF, one side may negotiate a speed different from the other side.
[src:ospf-routing/open-shortest-path-first] This can create an asymmetric routing on the link (Router 1 to Router 2 could cost '1' and the return path could cost '10'), which may lead to unintended consequences.
[src:ospf-routing/open-shortest-path-first] Metrics, however, are only directly comparable when of the same type.
[src:ospf-routing/open-shortest-path-first] Despite the expansion of addresses to 128 bits in IPv6, area and router identifications are still 32-bit numbers.
[src:ospf-routing/open-shortest-path-first] A customer can use OSPF over a MPLS VPN, where the service provider uses BGP or RIP as their interior gateway protocol.
[src:ospf-routing/open-shortest-path-first] When using OSPF over MPLS VPN, the VPN backbone becomes part of the OSPF backbone area 0.
[src:ospf-routing/open-shortest-path-first] In all areas, isolated copies of the IGP are run.
[src:ospf-routing/open-shortest-path-first] To achieve this, a modified OSPF-BGP redistribution is used.
[src:ospf-routing/open-shortest-path-first] All OSPF routes retain the source LSA type and metric.
[src:ospf-routing/open-shortest-path-first] To prevent loops, an optional DN bit is set by the service provider in LSAs from the provider equipment to indicate that a route has already been sent to the customer's equipment.
[src:ospf-routing/open-shortest-path-first] OSPF-TE is an extension to OSPF, extending the expressivity to allow for traffic engineering and use on non-IP networks.
[src:ospf-routing/open-shortest-path-first] Using OSPF-TE, more information about the topology can be exchanged using opaque LSA carrying type–length–value elements.
[src:ospf-routing/open-shortest-path-first] These extensions allow OSPF-TE to run completely out of band of the data plane network.
[src:ospf-routing/open-shortest-path-first] This means that it can also be used on non-IP networks, such as optical networks.
[src:ospf-routing/open-shortest-path-first] OSPF-TE is used in GMPLS networks as a means to describe the topology over which GMPLS paths can be established.
[src:ospf-routing/open-shortest-path-first] GMPLS uses its own path setup and forwarding protocols once it has the full network map.
[src:ospf-routing/open-shortest-path-first] In the Resource Reservation Protocol (RSVP), OSPF-TE is used for recording and flooding RSVP signaled bandwidth reservations for label-switched paths within the link-state database.
[src:ospf-routing/open-shortest-path-first] RFC 3717 documents work in optical routing for IP based on extensions to OSPF and IS-IS.
[src:ospf-routing/open-shortest-path-first] The Multicast Open Shortest Path First (MOSPF) protocol is an extension to OSPF to support multicast routing.
[src:ospf-routing/open-shortest-path-first] MOSPF allows routers to share information about group memberships.
[src:ospf-routing/open-shortest-path-first] OSPF is a widely deployed routing protocol that can converge a network in a few seconds and guarantee loop-free paths.
[src:ospf-routing/open-shortest-path-first] It has many features that allow the imposition of policies about the propagation of routes that may be appropriate to keep local, for load sharing, and for selective route importing.
[src:ospf-routing/open-shortest-path-first] IS-IS, in contrast, can be tuned for lower overhead in a stable network, the sort more common in ISP than enterprise networks.
[src:ospf-routing/open-shortest-path-first] There are some historical accidents that made IS-IS the preferred IGP for ISPs, but ISPs today may well choose to use the features of the now-efficient implementations of OSPF, after first considering the pros and cons of IS-IS in service provider environments.
[src:ospf-routing/open-shortest-path-first] OSPF can provide better load-sharing on external links than other IGPs.
[src:ospf-routing/open-shortest-path-first] When the default route to an ISP is injected into OSPF from multiple ASBRs as a Type I external route and the same external cost specified, other routers will go to the ASBR with the least path cost from its location.
[src:ospf-routing/open-shortest-path-first] This can be tuned further by adjusting the external cost.
[src:ospf-routing/open-shortest-path-first] If the default route from different ISPs is injected with different external costs, as a Type II external route, the lower-cost default becomes the primary exit and the higher-cost becomes the backup only.
